overspin.definition: To spin out to too great length; to protract unduly

overspread.definition: To spread over; to cover; as, the deluge overspread the earth
To be spread or scattered over

overstand.definition: To stand on the price or conditions of, so as to lose a sale; to lose by an extravagant price or hard conditions

overstate.definition: To state in too strong terms; to exaggerate

overstated.definition: represented as greater than is true or reasonable; exaggerated; as, They made overstated accusations of corruption

overstay.definition: To stay beyond the time or the limits of; as, to overstay the appointed time; to overstay one's welcome

overstep.definition: To step over or beyond; to transgress; as, to overstep the bounds of propriety

overstock.definition: To fill too full; to supply in excess; as, to overstock a market with goods, or a farm with cattle

overstrain.definition: To strain one's self to excess
To stretch or strain too much; as, to overstrain one's nerves

oversum.definition: A sum or quantity over; surplus

oversupply.definition: An excessive supply; a supply in excess of demand

overswell.definition: To swell or rise above; to overflow

overt.definition: Open to view; public; apparent; manifest.  Opposite of hidden
Not covert; open; public; manifest; as, an overt act of treason

overtake.definition: To come up with in a race, pursuit, progress, or motion
To surpass in production, achievement, etc.; as, although out of school for half a year due to illness, the student returned and overtook all the others to finish as valedictorian
To come upon from behind; to discover; to surprise; to capture; to overcome
Hence, figuratively, in the past participle (overtaken), drunken
To frustrate or render impossible or irrelevant; -- used mostly of plans, and commonly in the phrase overtaken by events; as, their careful marketing plan was overtaken by events

overtax.definition: To tax or to task too heavily; as, a job that overtaxed his physical energies

overtempt.definition: To tempt exceedingly, or beyond the power of resistance

overthrow.definition: To throw over; to overturn; to upset; to turn upside down
To cause to fall or to fail; to subvert; to defeat; to make a ruin of; to destroy; as, to overthrow a government
To throw (a baseball) beyond; to throw too high and too far; to overshoot{1}; as, the shortstop overthrew the first baseman
The act of overthrowing; the state of being overthrown; ruin
The act of throwing a ball too high, as over a player's head

overthwart.definition: Having a transverse position; placed or situated across; hence, opposite
Crossing in kind or disposition; perverse; adverse; opposing
Across; from alde to side of
That which is overthwart; an adverse circumstance; opposition

overthwartly.definition: In an overthwart manner; across; also, perversely

overthwartness.definition: The state of being overthwart; perverseness

overtime.definition: Time beyond, or in excess of, a limit; esp., extra working time
An extra period of time provided to play a game, beyond the end of the normal period allowed for the game, for the purpose of resolving a tie score; as, the team won in overtime

overtire.definition: To tire to excess; to exhaust

overtitle.definition: To give too high a title to

overtone.definition: One of the harmonics faintly heard with and at a higher frequency than a fundamental tone as it dies away, produced by some aliquot portion of the vibrating sting or column of air which yields the fundamental tone; one of the natural harmonic scale of tones, as the octave, twelfth, fifteenth, etc.; an aliquot or “partial” tone; a harmonic. See Harmonic, and Tone

overtop.definition: To rise above the top of; to exceed in height; to tower above
To go beyond; to transcend; to transgress
To make of less importance, or throw into the background, by superior excellence; to dwarf; to obscure

overtrade.definition: To trade beyond one's capital; to buy goods beyond the means of paying for or selling them; to overstock the market

overtrading.definition: The act or practice of buying goods beyond the means of payment; a glutting of the market

overtrow.definition: To be too trustful or confident; to trust too much

overture.definition: An opening or aperture; a recess; a chamber
A proposal; an offer; a proposition formally submitted for consideration, acceptance, or rejection
A composition, for a full orchestra, designed as an introduction to an oratorio, opera, or ballet, or as an independent piece; -- called in the latter case a concert overture
To make an overture to; as, to overture a religious body on some subject

overturn.definition: To turn or throw from a basis, foundation, or position; to overset; as, to overturn a carriage or a building
To subvert; to destroy; to overthrow
The act off overturning, or the state of being overturned or subverted; overthrow; as, an overturn of parties

overturnable.definition: Capable of being, or liable to be, overturned or subverted

overuse.definition: To use excessively; to use too often; as, scientists tend to overuse technical terms

overutilization.definition: exploitation to the point of diminishing returns

overutilize.definition: To exploit to the point of diminishing returns; to use excessively

overvaliant.definition: Having or showing undue valor or boldness; as, they stepped with overvaliant airs

overvalue.definition: To value excessively; to rate at too high a price

overview.definition: A brief summary of a topic, situation, or plan; an outline or survey{2}

overvote.definition: To outvote; to outnumber in votes given

overwasted.definition: Wasted or worn out; consumed; spent

overwatch.definition: To weary or exhaust by watching

overwax.definition: To wax or grow too rapidly or too much

overwear.definition: To wear too much; to wear out
Clothing worn over the ordinary indoor clothing, as overcoats, wraps, etc

overweary.definition: To weary too much; to tire out

overweather.definition: To expose too long to the influence of the weather

overween.definition: To think too highly or arrogantly; to regard one's own thinking or conclusions too highly; hence, to be egotistic, arrogant, or rash, in opinion; to think conceitedly; to presume

overweigh.definition: To exceed in weight; to overbalance; to weigh down

overweight.definition: Weight over and above what is required by law or custom
Having a weight in excess of what is normal, proper, or expected; as, the doctor recommends dieting to all his overweight patients; overweight luggage will incur an extra charge

overwhelm.definition: To cover over completely, as by a great wave; to overflow and bury beneath; to ingulf; hence, figuratively, to immerse and bear down; to overpower; to crush; to bury; to oppress, etc., overpoweringly
To project or impend over threateningly
To cause to surround, to cover

overwhelmed.definition: defeated easily by a greatly superior opponent

overwind.definition: To wind too tightly, as a spring, or too far, as a hoisting rope on a drum

overword.definition: To say in too many words; to express verbosely

overwork.definition: To work beyond the strength; to cause to labor too much or too long; to tire excessively; as, to overwork a horse
To fill too full of work; to crowd with labor
To work too much, or beyond one's strength
Work in excess of the usual or stipulated time or quantity; extra work; also, excessive labor

overworn.definition: Worn out or subdued by toil; worn out so as to be trite

overwrest.definition: To wrest or force from the natural or proper position

overwrought.definition: Extremely agitated or excited; overexcited; -- of people

ovicapsule.definition: The outer layer of a Graafian follicle

ovicell.definition: One of the dilatations of the body wall of Bryozoa in which the ova sometimes undergo the first stages of their development. See Illust. of Chilostoma

ovicular.definition: Of or pertaining to an egg

ovicyst.definition: The pouch in which incubation takes place in some Tunicata

ovidian.definition: Of or pertaining to the Latin poet Ovid; resembling the style of Ovid

oviducal.definition: Of or pertaining to oviducts; as, oviducal glands

oviduct.definition: A tube, or duct, for the passage of ova from the ovary to the exterior of the animal or to the part where further development takes place.  In mammals the oviducts are also called Fallopian tubes

oviferous.definition: Egg-bearing; -- applied particularly to certain receptacles, as in Crustacea, that retain the eggs after they have been excluded from the formative organs, until they are hatched

oviform.definition: Having the form or figure of an egg; egg-shaped; as, an oviform leaf

ovine.definition: Of or pertaining to sheep; consisting of sheep

ovipara.definition: An artificial division of vertebrates, including those that lay eggs; -- opposed to Vivipara

oviparity.definition: Generation by means of ova. See Generation

oviparous.definition: Producing young from eggs; as, an oviparous animal, in which the egg is generally separated from the animal, and hatched after exclusion; -- opposed to viviparous

oviposit.definition: To lay or deposit eggs; -- said esp. of insects

ovipositing.definition: The depositing of eggs, esp. by insects

ovipositor.definition: The organ with which many insects and some other animals deposit their eggs.  Some ichneumon files have a long ovipositor fitted to pierce the eggs or larvae of other insects, in order to lay their own eggs within the same

ovisac.definition: A Graafian follicle; any sac containing an ovum or ova

ovism.definition: The old theory that the egg contains the whole embryo of the future organism and the germs of all subsequent offsprings and is merely awakened to activity by the spermatozoon; -- opposed to spermism or animalculism

ovist.definition: A believer in ovism.  Same as Ovulist

ovoflavin.definition: An uncommon name for riboflavin, also called vitamin B2

ovoid.definition: Resembling an egg in shape; egg-shaped; ovate; as, an ovoidal apple
A solid resembling an egg in shape

ovolo.definition: A round, convex molding. See Illust. of Column

ovology.definition: That branch of natural history which treats of the origin and functions of eggs

ovotesttis.definition: An organ which produces both ova and spermatozoids; an hermaphrodite gland

ovoviviparous.definition: Oviparous, but hatching the egg while it is within the body, as some fishes and reptiles

ovular.definition: Relating or belonging to an ovule; as, an ovular growth

ovulate.definition: To produce ova and discharge them from an ovary or ovarian follicle

ovulation.definition: The formation of ova or eggs in the ovary, and the discharge of the same.  In the human female the discharge occurs about halfway between menstruation times

ovule.definition: The rudiment of a seed.  It grows from a placenta, and consists of a soft nucleus within two delicate coatings.  The attached base of the ovule is the hilum, the coatings are united with the nucleus at the chalaza, and their minute orifice is the foramen

ovulist.definition: A believer in the theory (called encasement theory), current during the last century, that the egg was the real animal germ, and that at the time of fecundation the spermatozoa simply gave the impetus which caused the unfolding of the egg, in which all generations were inclosed one within the other. Also called ovist

ovum.definition: A more or less spherical and transparent cell, which by a process of multiplication and growth develops into a mass of cells, constituting a new individual like the parent; an egg, spore, germ, or germ cell. See Illust. of Mycropyle
One of the series of egg-shaped ornaments into which the ovolo is often carved

owe.definition: To possess; to have, as the rightful owner; to own

To have or possess, as something derived or bestowed; to be obliged to ascribe (something to some source); to be indebted or obliged for; as, he owed his wealth to his father; he owed his victory to his lieutenants

To have or be under an obigation to restore, pay, or render (something) in return or compensation for something received; to be indebted in the sum of; as, the subject owes allegiance; the fortunate owe assistance to the unfortunate
To have an obligation to (some one) on account of something done or received; to be indebted to; as, to owe the grocer for supplies, or a laborer for services

owelty.definition: Equality; -- sometimes written ovelty and ovealty

owenite.definition: A follower of Robert Owen, who tried to reorganize society on a socialistic basis, and established an industrial community on the Clyde, Scotland, and, later, a similar one in Indiana

owing.definition: Had or held under obligation of paying; due
Had or experienced as a consequence, result, issue, etc.; ascribable; -- with to; as, misfortunes are often owing to vices; his failure was owing to speculations

owl.definition: Any species of raptorial birds of the family Strigidae.  They have large eyes and ears, and a conspicuous circle of feathers around each eye.  They are mostly nocturnal in their habits
A variety of the domestic pigeon
To carry wool or sheep out of England
Hence, to carry on any contraband trade

owler.definition: One who owls; esp., one who conveys contraband goods. See Owling, n

owlery.definition: An abode or a haunt of owls

owlet.definition: A small owl; especially, the European species (Athene noctua), and the California flammulated owlet (Megascops flammeolus)

owling.definition: The offense of transporting wool or sheep out of England contrary to the statute formerly existing

owlish.definition: Resembling, or characteristic of, an owl

own.definition: To grant; to acknowledge; to admit to be true; to confess; to recognize in a particular character; as, we own that we have forfeited your love

Belonging to; belonging exclusively or especially to; peculiar; -- most frequently following a possessive pronoun, as my, our, thy, your, his, her, its, their, in order to emphasize or intensify the idea of property, peculiar interest, or exclusive ownership; as, my own father; my own composition; my own idea; at my own price
To hold as property; to have a legal or rightful title to; to be the proprietor or possessor of; to possess; as, to own a house

owned.definition: having an owner; often used in combination; as, state-owned railways.  Opposite of unowned

owner.definition: One who owns; a rightful proprietor; one who has the legal or rightful title, whether he is the possessor or not

owner-driver.definition: a motorist who owns the vehicle that he/she drives

owner-occupied.definition: lived in by the owner; -- of dwellings

owner-occupier.definition: a occupant who owns the home that he/she lives in

ownership.definition: The state of being an owner; the right to own; exclusive right of possession; legal or just claim or title; proprietorship

ox.definition: The male of bovine quadrupeds, especially the domestic animal when castrated and grown to its full size, or nearly so. The word is also applied, as a general name, to any species of bovine animals, male and female

oxalacetate.definition: a salt or ester of oxalacetic acid

oxalan.definition: A complex nitrogenous substance C3N3H5O3 obtained from alloxan (or when urea is fused with ethyl oxamate), as a stable white crystalline powder; -- called also oxaluramide

oxalantin.definition: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance (C6H4N4O5)  obtained by the reduction of parabanic acid; -- called also leucoturic acid

oxalethyline.definition: A poisonous nitrogenous base (C6H10N2) obtained indirectly from oxamide as a thick transparent oil which has a strong narcotic odor, and a physiological action resembling that of atropine. It is probably related to pyridine

oxalic.definition: Pertaining to, derived from, or contained in, sorrel, or oxalis; specifically, designating an acid found in, and characteristic of, oxalis, and also certain plant of the Buckwheat family

oxalis.definition: A genus of plants, mostly herbs, with acid-tasting trifoliolate or multifoliolate leaves; -- called also wood sorrel

oxalite.definition: A yellow mineral consisting of oxalate of iron

oxaluric.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid related to the ureids, and obtained from parabanic acid as a white silky crystalline substance

oxalyl.definition: A hydrocarbon radical (C2O2) regarded as a residue of oxalic acid and occurring in derivatives of it

oxamethane.definition: Ethyl oxamate, obtained as a white scaly crystalline powder

oxamethylane.definition: Methyl oxamate, obtained as a pearly white crystalline substance

oxamic.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, an acid NH2.CO.CO.HO obtained as a fine crystalline powder, intermediate between oxalic acid and oxamide. Its ammonium salt is obtained by boiling oxamide with ammonia

oxamide.definition: A white crystalline neutral substance (C2O2(NH2)2) obtained by treating ethyl oxalate with ammonia. It is the acid amide of oxalic acid.  Formerly called also oxalamide

oxamidine.definition: One of a series of bases containing the amido and the isonitroso groups united to the same carbon atom

oxanilamide.definition: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance, obtained indirectly by the action of cyanogen on aniline, and regarded as an anilide of oxamic acid; -- called also phenyl oxamide

oxanilic.definition: Pertaining to, or derived from, oxalic acid and aniline; -- used to designate an acid obtained in white crystalline scales by heating these substances together

oxanilide.definition: A white crystalline substance, resembling oxanilamide, obtained by heating aniline oxalate, and regarded as a double anilide of oxalic acid; -- called also diphenyl oxamide

oxbane.definition: A poisonous bulbous plant (Buphane toxicaria) of the Cape of Good Hope

oxbow.definition: A frame of wood, bent into the shape of the letter U, and embracing an ox's neck as a kind of collar, the upper ends passing through the bar of the yoke; also, anything so shaped, as a bend in a river

oxeye.definition: The oxeye daisy. See under Daisy
A titmouse, especially the great titmouse (Parus major) and the blue titmouse (Parus coeruleus)

oxeyed.definition: Having large, full eyes, like those of an ox

oxford.definition: Of or pertaining to the city or university of Oxford, England

oxhead.definition: Literally, the head of an ox (emblem of cuckoldom); hence, a dolt; a blockhead

oxheart.definition: A large heart-shaped cherry, either black, red, or white

oxhide.definition: The skin of an ox, or leather made from it
A measure of land. See 3d Hide

oxidability.definition: Capability of being converted into an oxide

oxidable.definition: Capable of being converted into an oxide

oxidation.definition: The act or process of oxidizing, or the state or result of being oxidized

oxidative.definition: of or pertaining to oxidation; accompanied by oxidation

oxidator.definition: A contrivance for causing a current of air to impinge on the flame of the Argand lamp; -- called also oxygenator

oxide.definition: A binary compound of oxygen with an atom or radical, or a compound which is regarded as binary; as, iron oxide, ethyl oxide, nitrogen oxide, etc

oxidization.definition: The process of oxidizing; the addition of oxygen to a compound with a loss of electrons.  The process always occurs accompanied by reduction

oxidize.definition: To combine with oxygen, or subject to the action of oxygen, or of an oxidizing agent

oxidized.definition: combined with or having undergone a chemical reaction with oxygen; as, the oxidized form of iodine

oxidizer.definition: An agent employed in oxidation, or which facilitates or brings about combination with oxygen; as, nitric acid, chlorine, bromine, etc., are strong oxidizers

oxidulated.definition: Existing in the state of a protoxide; -- said of an oxide

oxime.definition: One of a series of isonitroso derivatives obtained by the action of hydroxylamine on aldehydes or ketones

oxindol.definition: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance (C8H7NO) of the indol group, obtained by the reduction of dioxindol.  It is a so-called lactam compound

oxiodic.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, certain compounds of iodine and oxygen

oxlike.definition: Characteristic of, or like, an ox

oxlip.definition: The great cowslip (Primula veris, var. elatior)

oxonian.definition: Of or relating to the city or the university of Oxford, England
A student or graduate of Oxford University, in England

oxonic.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid (C4H5N3O4) not known in the free state, but obtained, in combination with its salts, by a slow oxidation of uric acid, to which it is related

oxpecker.definition: An African bird of the genus Buphaga; the beefeater

oxshoe.definition: A shoe for oxen, consisting of a flat piece of iron nailed to the hoof

oxtongue.definition: A widespread European weed (Picris echioides formerly Helminthia echioides) with spiny tongue-shaped leaves and yellow flowers.  The name is applied to several plants, from the shape and roughness of their leaves; as, Anchusa officinalis, a kind of bugloss, and Helminthia echioides, both European herbs.  It has been naturalized in the U. S

oxyacetic.definition: Hydroxyacetic; designating an acid called also glycolic acid

oxyacetylene.definition: Of or pertaining to a mixture of oxygen and actylene; as, an oxyacetylene torch

oxyacetylene torch.definition: A torch designed to mix oxygen and actylene at its tip, to create a very hot flame for welding, cutting steel, and other metal working

oxyacid.definition: An acid containing oxygen, as chloric acid or sulphuric acid; -- contrasted with the hydracids, which contain no oxygen, as hydrochloric acid. See Acid, and Hydroxy-

oxybenzoic.definition: Hydroxybenzoic; pertaining to, or designating, any one of several hydroxyl derivatives of benzonic acid, of which the commonest is salicylic acid

oxybromic.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, certain compounds of oxygen and bromine

oxybutyric.definition: Hydroxybutyric; designating any one of a group of metameric acids ((C3H6.OH).CO2H)

oxycalcium.definition: Of or pertaining to oxygen and calcium; as, the oxycalcium light. See Drummond light

oxychloric.definition: Of, pertaining to, or designating in general, certain compounds containing oxygen and chlorine

oxychloride.definition: A ternary compound of oxygen and chlorine; as, plumbic oxychloride

oxycrate.definition: A Mixture of water and vinegar

oxygen.definition: A colorless, tasteless, odorless, gaseous element of atomic number 8, occurring in the free state in the atmosphere, of which it forms about 23 per cent by weight and about 21 per cent by volume, being slightly heavier than nitrogen.  Symbol O.  Atomic weight 15.9994

oxygenate.definition: To unite, or cause to combine, with oxygen; to treat with oxygen; to oxidize; as, oxygenated water (hydrogen dioxide)

oxygenation.definition: The act or process of combining or of treating with oxygen; oxidation

oxygenic.definition: Pertaining to, containing, or resembling, oxygen; producing oxygen

oxygon.definition: A triangle having three acute angles

oxyhydrogen.definition: Of, pertaining to, or consisting of, a mixture of oxygen and hydrogen at over 5000° F

oxyhydrogen light.definition: A light produced by the incandescence of some substances, esp. lime, in the oxyhydrogen flame.  Coal gas (producing the oxygas light), or the vapor of ether (oxyether light) or methylated spirit (oxyspirit light), may be substituted for hydrogen

oxymel.definition: A mixture of honey, water, vinegar, and spice, boiled to a sirup

oxymethylene.definition: Formic aldehyde, regarded as a methylene derivative

oxymoron.definition: A figure in which an epithet of a contrary signification is added to a word; e. g., cruel kindness; laborious idleness

oxymuriate.definition: A salt of the supposed oxymuriatic acid; a chloride

oxymuriatic.definition: Pertaining to, or consisting of, oxygen and muriatic acid, that is, hydrochloric acid

oxyntic.definition: Acid; producing acid; -- applied especially to certain glands and cells in the stomach

oxyphenic.definition: Pertaining to, or designating, the phenol formerly called oxyphenic acid, and now oxyphenol and pyrocatechin. See Pyrocatechin

oxyphenol.definition: A phenol, C6H4(OH)2, produced by the distillation of catechin; called also oxyphenic acid, and now pyrocatechin

oxyquinoline.definition: Hydroxy quinoline; a phenol derivative of quinoline, -- called also carbostyril

oxyrrhodine.definition: A mixture of two parts of the oil of roses with one of the vinegar of roses

oxysalt.definition: A salt of an oxyacid, as a sulphate

oxysulphide.definition: A ternary compound of oxygen and sulphur

oxytoluene.definition: One of three hydroxy derivatives of toluene, called the cresols. See Cresol

oxytone.definition: Having an acute sound; (Gr. Gram.), having an acute accent on the last syllable
A word having the acute accent on the last syllable

oyer.definition: A hearing or an inspection, as of a deed, bond, etc., as when a defendant in court prays oyer of a writing

oyez.definition: Hear; attend; -- a term used by criers of courts to secure silence before making a proclamation.  It is repeated three times

oyster.definition: Any marine bivalve mollusk of the genus Ostrea. They are usually found adhering to rocks or other fixed objects in shallow water along the seacoasts, or in brackish water in the mouth of rivers. The common European oyster (Ostrea edulis), and the American oyster (Ostrea Virginiana), are the most important species
A name popularly given to the delicate morsel contained in a small cavity of the bone on each side of the lower part of the back of a fowl

oyster-green.definition: A green membranous seaweed (Ulva) often found growing on oysters but common on stones, piles, etc

oystercatcher.definition: Any one of several species of wading birds of the genus Haematopus having stout legs and bill and mostly black-and-white plumage, which frequent seashores and feed upon oysters and other shellfish.  The European species (Haematopus ostralegus), the common American species (Haematopus palliatus), and the California, or black, oyster catcher (Haematopus Bachmani) are the best known

ozena.definition: A discharge of fetid matter from the nostril, particularly if associated with ulceration of the soft parts and disease of the bones of the nose

ozocerite.definition: A waxlike mineral resin; -- sometimes called native paraffin, and mineral wax

ozonation.definition: The act of treating with ozone; also, the act of converting into, or producing, ozone; ozonization

ozone.definition: A colorless gaseous substance (O3) obtained (as by the silent discharge of electricity in oxygen) as an allotropic form of oxygen, containing three atoms in the molecule.  It is a strong oxidizer, and probably exists in the air, though by the ordinary tests it is liable to be confused with certain other substances, as hydrogen dioxide, or certain oxides of nitrogen.  It derives its name from its peculiar odor, which resembles that of weak chlorine

ozone paper.definition: Paper coated with starch and potassium iodine, also called starch-iodide paper. It turns blue when exposed to ozone

ozonic.definition: Pertaining to, resembling, or containing, ozone

ozonification.definition: The act or process of producing, or of subjecting to the action of, ozone

ozonize.definition: To convert into ozone, as oxygen

ozonizer.definition: An apparatus or agent for the production or application of ozone

ozonometer.definition: An instrument for ascertaining the amount of ozone in the atmosphere, or in any gaseous mixture

ozonometric.definition: Pertaining to, or used for, the determination of the amount of ozone; of or relating to ozonometry

ozonometry.definition: The measurement or determination of the quantity of ozone

ozonoscope.definition: An apparatus employed to indicate the presence, or the amount, of ozone

ozonoscopic.definition: Serving to indicate the presence or the amount of ozone
